lzh_formatted:
  title: 再辭箋
  author: 尹淮
  language: lzh
  text: 草土臣尹某。稽顙上言。臣於宣德八年三月十三日。上書陳乞辭免起復恩命。至本月十五日。敬蒙批答不允。臣某不勝隕越。更陳卑抱者。伏以敷衽陳辭。兾遵禮訓。批章優答。尙阻兪音。敢竭愚衷。再瀆宸聽。伏念臣嚴父早逝。慈顔是依。軒渠偏膝下之憐。遊宦弊手中之線。蘭陔罰酷。空傷隙駟之難留。風樹悲纏。益感林烏之不若。唯跂及衰絰之中制。庶小酬鞠育之深恩。甫過練期。忽承綸命。特除文史之舊任。又賜諄諭之恩言。然三年通喪。乃萬世之大法。則一時變禮。豈平日之可行。非徒無補於聖朝。實亦有虧於名敎。伏望主上殿下。擴乾坤包容之度。察草土不忍之情。推錫類之孝思。寢奪哀於權典。報親日少。願終制以爲期。事國時長。顧移忠之未晚。
korean:
  title: 재사전
  author: 윤회
  language: kor
  text: 초토 신 윤회는 이마를 조아리며 글월을 올리옵니다. 신은 선덕(宣德) 8년 3월 13일에 글월을 올려 기복(起復)하라 하시는 은명(恩命)을 면하기를 청하였사온바, 윤허하시지 않는 비답(批答)을 공경히 받자왔기로, 신 회는 놀라움을 이기지 못하와 다시 소회를 아뢰는 것이옵니다. 엎드려 생각하옵건대, 옷깃을 여미고 말씀을 아뢰어 예법에 따르기를 바랐사오나, 비장(批章)의 회답이 아직도 유음(兪音)을 아끼시옵기로 감히 우견을 다하여 두 번째 신청(宸聽)을 모독하옵니다. 엎드려 생각하오면, 신은 부친을 여의고 모친에게 의지하여 웃음으로 슬하의 사랑을 두루 받았사옵고, 손수 지어준 옷을 입고 벼슬길에 다녔사오나, 난해(蘭陔)의 벌(罰)이 흑심하여 세월이 덧없음을 슬퍼하고, 풍수(風樹)의 설움이 얽히어 더욱 숲속의 까마귀만도 못하옴을 느끼었사옵니다. 오직 상복의 제도를 마치어 길러준 은혜를 조금이라도 보답할까 하였사온데 겨우 1년을 지내자 문득 윤명(綸命)을 받자오니, 특별히 문사(文史)의 구직(舊職)을 제수하시고 또 온화하신 은언(恩言)을 주시었사옵니다. 그러하오나 3년의 통상(通喪)은 만세의 큰 법이옵고, 일시의 변칙된 예를 어찌 평시에 행할 수 있겠사옵니까. 한갓 성조께 보익됨이 없을 뿐만 아니오라, 실로 명교에 이지러짐이 있을 것이옵니다. 엎드려 바라옵건대, 주상전하께서는 천지의 포용하는 도량을 넓히시고 초토(草土)의 차마 못하는 정곡을 양찰하시와 석류(錫類)의 효도를 미루어, 권전(權典)으로써 슬픔을 빼앗지 말으시오면 자친을 위하는 날은 적사오니 상기를 마치는 것을 기한(期限)할 수 있고, 나라를 섬기는 시기는 길며 충성을 옮기는 것이 늦지 않을 줄 아옵니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0450_010_0420&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Second Petition for Exemption
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant Yun Hoe bows his forehead to the ground and respectfully submits this memorial.

    On the thirteenth day of the third month in the eighth year of Xuande, your servant submitted a petition requesting exemption from the gracious command to resume office during mourning. When the fifteenth day of this month arrived, your servant received the imperial response denying this request. Overwhelmed by this unexpected verdict, I now dare to present my heartfelt sentiments once more, humbly seeking to bring my true feelings before the throne.

    I had hoped that by carefully presenting my words in accordance with propriety, the imperial response would grant me this wish. Yet the reply remains withheld, and so I am compelled to lay bare my humble sincerity and once more disturb the imperial ear.

    Reflecting upon my circumstances: I lost my father early in life and have depended upon my mother's care. Through her gentle affection, I have known the boundless love of a parent's heart. I have worn the garments she made with her own hands as I ventured into service. Yet the harsh circumstances of mourning have wounded me deeply, and I grieve how fleeting the days have become—even the raven in the forest is more at peace than I. I sought only to complete the full period of mourning, hoping to repay in some small measure the profound debt of gratitude I owe to those who raised me.

    Barely had I passed the first year when an imperial command suddenly arrived. The throne has graciously appointed me to my former position and bestowed words of warm encouragement. Yet the three-year mourning period is an eternal law, binding for all ages. How can one temporarily overturn propriety and still call it right conduct in ordinary times? This would not only fail to serve the throne, but would also bring shame upon the teachings of virtue.

    I humbly beseech Your Majesty to extend the vast compassion of heaven and earth, to understand the feelings of your humble servant who cannot bear to abandon this duty, to extend the benevolence shown to all creatures through filial piety, and to refrain from using expedient measures to diminish my mourning. The days I can offer to my parents are few—grant me to complete this observance as my final act. The years I can serve the state are long, and my loyalty need not be delayed.
  footnotes:
    - The eighth year of Xuande refers to 1433 CE during the reign of the Xuande Emperor of Ming China, though this memorial was likely submitted during the Korean Joseon dynasty period.
    - The reference to 'three-year mourning' reflects the Confucian ritual of extended filial mourning, during which a son should withdraw from public office.
    - The imagery of 'wind and trees' and 'raven in the forest' are classical allusions expressing sorrow—references to the impossibility of repaying parents after their death and the isolation of mourning.
